		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I guess that once you have the basic framework ready (video and audio), the rest is just logic, and since CPU emulation is much more accurate than PPU or APU emulation, emulators should be enough for the task.</div>
<br />
<br />Yeah that's usually true.
<br />
<br />I've taken the opposite approach, usually when I was making the most progress I used my ROM emulator.  Then I can just hit F9, reset the NES after a second or 2, and not even have to leave the code editor.  Saves time.  I also found it motivating to see/hear it running on the system, and of course the screen looks very different from emulators.  NEStopia's tv mode seems closer to it.  It also allowed me to eventually use my own boards that aren't emulated.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


