		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Memblers wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I've taken the opposite approach, usually when I was making the most progress I used my ROM emulator.  Then I can just hit F9, reset the NES after a second or 2, and not even have to leave the code editor.</div>
<br />That's pretty cool! But there's the fact that you have zero debugging capabilities on a real NES. I mean, other than those you've programmed into the game yourself, but it's still much easier to look at FCEUXD's hex editor than writing a subroutine to display numbers somewhere on the screen. And there are kinds of debugging that I don't think are even possible with just the real console (CPU tracing, watching name tables, things like that).

		

		</td>
	</tr>
